85 (6) The Alabama Department of Finance.
86 (7) The Alabama Department of Insurance.
87 (8) The Alabama Department of Public Health.
88 (9) The Alabama Department of Transportation.
89 (10) The Alabama Emergency Management Agency.
90 (11) The Alabama Forestry Commission.
91 (12) The Alabama State Military Department.
92 (13) The Alabama Office of Information Technology.
93 (14) The Alabama State Law Enforcement Agency.
94 (15) The Alabama Public Service Commission
95 (c) Non-voting members of council may be appointed by
96 the Governor and should include representatives of local
97 government; critical infrastructure owners and operators;
98 business, industry, and insurance sectors; and other state
99 agencies.
100 (d) The council membership shall be inclusive and
101 reflect the racial, gender, geographic, urban, rural, and
102 economic diversity of the state.
103 Section 3. The duties of the Alabama Resilience Council
104 shall be as follows:
105 (a) Develop strategies to guide statewide resilience
106 efforts by prioritizing objectives reflecting pressing
107 resilience challenges. To this end, the council shall
108 regularly convene government and private-sector stakeholders
109 with different perspectives and interests to facilitate
110 planning across jurisdictions and sectors and thereby to avoid
111 cascading failures. The council shall develop principles to
112 guide the work of state government in carrying out its
Page 4

guide the work of state government in carrying out its
HB179 INTRODUCED
113 resilience initiatives.
114 (b) Assist the Chief Resilience Officer in the
115 development, maintenance, and implementation of the statewide
116 resilience plan.
117 (c) Solicit participation of the private sector in
118 programs to collectively strengthen the resilience of
119 businesses and communities. The council shall engage the
120 private sector to reduce costs from lost productivity and
121 pursue joint, public-private efforts to avoid infrastructure
122 damages.
123 (d) Improve the public’s ability to assess risk
124 management alternatives by reducing the complexity of risk
125 information for non-technical audiences, by generating and
126 sharing reliable information that helps decisionmakers
127 identify and select risk-reduction alternatives, and by
128 providing guidance about assistance programs and funding
129 opportunities based on needs, cost effectiveness, feasibility,
130 potential resources, and returns on investment.
131 (e) Develop, pursue, and support federal and state
132 policies and programs that promote innovative and flexible
133 solutions for achieving individual, community, and statewide
134 resilience.
135 (f) Provide support and assistance in the preparation
136 and maintenance of the state hazard mitigation plan, as
137 contemplated by the federal Disaster Mitigation Act of 2000,
138 42 U.S.C § 5121, et seq., or successor federal statute;
139 provided that the Alabama Emergency Management Agency shall be
140 responsible for administrative maintenance and day-to-day
Page 5

responsible for administrative maintenance and day-to-day
HB179 INTRODUCED
141 execution of the plan.
142 (g) Identify and pursue funding opportunities to
143 promote resilience in the State of Alabama.
144 Section 4. (a) The council shall be led by a Chair,
145 Vice-Chair, Co-Chairs, or other leadership positions from
146 within the voting membership on the council. Leadership
147 positions shall be appointed by the Governor and shall serve
148 at the pleasure of the Governor.
149 (b) The council shall develop, adopt, and maintain
150 bylaws governing its activities; provided the bylaws are
151 consistent with the provisions of this Act. At its discretion,
152 the council may establish working groups or subcommittees.
153 (c) The council shall meet at least twice each year and
154 may meet more frequently upon the call of the chair, subject
155 to the Open Meetings Act. Members of the council may
156 participate in a meeting of the council by means of telephone
157 conference, video conference, or similar communications
158 equipment by means of which all individuals participating in
159 the meeting may hear each other at the same time.
160 Participation by electronic means shall constitute presence in
161 person at a meeting for all purposes.
162 (d) Members of the council shall serve without
163 compensation except members who are public officials or public
164 employees may elect to receive the per diem and travel
165 allowance authorized by state law for persons traveling on
166 official state business.
167 Section 5. (a) The Governor shall appoint a Chief
168 Resilience Officer to coordinate the activities of the council
Page 6

Resilience Officer to coordinate the activities of the council
HB179 INTRODUCED
169 established pursuant to Section 2 and lead the development,
170 maintenance, and implementation of the statewide resilience
171 Plan. The Chief Resilience Officer shall serve at the pleasure
172 of the Governor.
173 (b) The duties of the Chief Resilience Officer shall be
174 as follows:
175 (1) Conduct a comprehensive inventory of Alabama’s
176 resilience assets.
177 (2) Identify areas of collaboration among state
178 agencies, areas of overlap, and potential shareable resources.
179 (3) Review resilience programs from both inside Alabama
180 and among comparable states.
181 (4) Engage state agencies to examine how to best
182 collect, organize, analyze, and communicate data in ways that
183 advance Alabama’s resilience principles.
184 (5) Identify and enhance state agency knowledge of
185 statewide resilience efforts.
186 (6) Identify and pursue funding through federal, state,
187 and private opportunities to promote resilience in the State
188 of Alabama.
189 (c) The Office of the Chief Resilience Officer may
190 contract for professional services in the same manner as any
191 state agency. Upon the approval of the Governor, the Chief
192 Resilience Officer may hire staff as determined necessary to
193 carry out the duties of the Chief Resilience Officer and the
194 council.
195 Section 6. (a) The Chief Resilience Officer shall
196 develop, maintain, and implement a statewide resilience plan,
Page 7

develop, maintain, and implement a statewide resilience plan,
HB179 INTRODUCED
197 with the general oversight and input from the council. The
198 plan shall include the following components:
199 (1) Statewide Comprehensive Risk and Vulnerability
200 Assessment. The plan shall evaluate the impacts of extreme
201 weather and disasters; assess current and future risks across
202 various hazards using historical data and future scenarios
203 while factoring in land and water management practices; and
204 examine effects on communities, infrastructure, the economy,
205 and the environment. Additionally, a vulnerability assessment
206 shall identify the social, economic, and environmental systems
207 most at risk. It shall analyze risk exposure, potential costs,
208 and impacts on state assets, government functions, local
209 economies, and critical natural systems.
210 (2) Resilience Actions. The plan shall provide a
211 prioritized list of resilience actions to address
212 vulnerabilities, detailing their benefits, costs, and
213 implementation timeline. Priority shall be given first to
214 actions that reduce state costs associated with historic and
215 persistent challenges or vulnerabilities that have calculable
216 costs or expenditures and that remediate or prevent critical
217 infrastructure failures that threaten public health, impair
218 essential services, or place the state at risk of federal
219 enforcement. Priority shall also be given to actions that
220 effectively mitigate the impacts of future disasters,
221 particularly those that provide multiple co-benefits, such as
222 enhancing environmental stewardship, economic stability, or
223 public health. Resilience actions that incorporate or restore
224 natural features to achieve risk mitigation benefits shall
Page 8

natural features to achieve risk mitigation benefits shall
HB179 INTRODUCED
225 also be prioritized, provided they are cost-effective and
226 demonstrate long-term advantages over alternative approaches.
227 The plan shall also outline how these actions align with
228 existing efforts by state agencies, local governments, and
229 other entities, ensuring they complement the state hazard
230 mitigation plan. Alabama state agencies engaged in resilience
231 activities shall report those activities to the Chief
232 Resilience Officer.
233 (3) Community Preparedness. The plan shall include
234 strategies to enhance community awareness to prepare for, and
235 protect against, hazards; to enable greater understanding of
236 personal risks; to educate residents of the state about how to
237 mitigate risks; and to increase knowledge of resources
238 available for mitigation efforts.
239 (4) Implementation Strategy. The plan shall include an
240 implementation strategy outlining how resilience actions will
241 be enacted, funded, and tracked. It shall define roles,
242 responsibilities, timelines, and metrics while prioritizing
243 actions for high-risk vulnerabilities. The strategy shall also
244 support partnerships, provide technical assistance, and ensure
245 public access to data for planning and decision-making.
246 (b) The initial plan shall be completed within two
247 years of the Governor appointing a Chief Resilience Officer
248 and shall be reviewed and updated at least every two years
249 thereafter to ensure its continued effectiveness and
250 relevance.
251 Section 7. There is created a fund in the State
252 Treasury to be designated the “Alabama Resilience Council
